Patch Set 3:

I do not 100% understand the implementation and goal of generic_error_remove_page(). I assume that it is safe if some funcion in generic_error_remove_page() clear the page with all zero (please correct me if I am wrong). Let's assume that I change some method of Lustre to clear tha page or poison the page(I am not sure which method can do that, maybe mapping->a_ops->freepage?). Then the following codes are dangerous:

		if (PageUptodate(lnb[i].lnb_page)) {
			cache_hits++;
		} else {
			cache_misses++;
			osd_iobuf_add_page(iobuf, lnb[i].lnb_page);
		}

		if (cache == 0)
			generic_error_remove_page(inode->i_mapping,
						  lnb[i].lnb_page);

If cache is zero, and the page i is uptodate, then generic_error_remove_page() will poison the page, and latter osd_do_bio() won't read back the page with correct data. And then, we get data with wrong data! I am not sure that is possible or not. It depends on what we can do in generic_error_remove_page(). If we can clear/poison page in generic_error_remove_page(), then that is a problem...

Patch Set 3:

generic_error_remove_page() doesn't clear data. it should be trivial to check: modify the code to call generic_error_remove_page() and verify the page's content right after.

int generic_error_remove_page(struct address_space *mapping, struct page *page)
{
	if (!mapping)
		return -EINVAL;
	/*
	 * Only punch for normal data pages for now.
	 * Handling other types like directories would need more auditing.
	 */
	if (!S_ISREG(mapping->host->i_mode))
		return -EIO;
	return truncate_inode_page(mapping, page);
}

there is no point to modify page's content when it's being removed from the cache.

the idea to remove pages from mapping is to stay as close to cacheless design (in 1.8) as possible. so that even if at some point we allow few threads to access same data (now serialized with PG_locked), then still the window when it's cached is minimal.

from functional point of view I still don't see any problem with removing pages from mapping early. please correct me with a test case or code.
